{
  "answer": "**San Hyan Mahajnana, Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis Shaiva tantric text compares the *puruṣa* (the Self) trapped in the ocean of *saṃsāra* (worldly suffering) to a *nāga* (serpent) terrified amid the waters.[^2] The sacred syllable *oṃkāra* is the *Garuḍa* (eagle) that lifts it to *śivapada* (Shiva's abode).[^3]\n\nThe verse names *puruṣa* as *nāga* and *oṃkāra* as *Garuḍa*:\n\n> *In the terrible ocean of saṃsāra, puruṣa is situated like a nāga. Knowing oṃkāra to be Garuḍa [...] for the effort [...] // 64*[^4]\n\nThe prose states that *oṃkāra* brings the Self (*puruṣa*) to *śivapada*:\n\n> The likeness of the revered *puruṣa* is one who is in the middle of the waters, terrified like a serpent. The holy *oṃkāra* is named Garuḍa. He is the one who brings the revered *puruṣa* to *śivapada*.[^5]\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, ch. 1, [full chapter](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, ch. 1, [p-7b2370](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-7b2370).\n\n[^3]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, ch. 1, [paragraphs p-7b2370 to p-d9dbdf](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-7b2370).\n\n[^4]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, ch. 1, [p-7b2370](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-7b2370).\n\n[^5]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, ch. 1, [p-d9dbdf](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-d9dbdf). See also [p-100b1c](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-100b1c): \"In the heart, there is what is called *śivapada* (the abode of Shiva). The holy *oṃkāra* is the supreme void, very subtle.\"",
